etymologies: early 17th century; earliest use found in Randle Cotgrave (fl. 1587–?1630), lexicographer. From classical Latin prōgenerāt-, past participial stem of prōgenerāre to beget, give birth to from prō- + generāre. Compare French †progenier to engender

definitions: To beget; to give birth to; (in extended use) to originate, give rise to. Also occasionally without object: to reproduce.
